INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a983a77c-3e63-4e59-9724-aea8a3b03cce',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Express Project Structure — MVC Is Holding You Back$escape$,
  $escape$The classic MVC layout (`controllers/`, `models/`, `routes/`) scatters a single feature across three directories. When you touch `UserController`, `UserModel`, and `userRoutes.js` for every change, you're paying a navigation tax. Vertical slice flips this: one folder owns everything for one feature.

In Express, a vertical slice for `users` lives in `src/features/users/` and contains `users.router.js`, `users.controller.js`, `users.service.js`, and `users.repository.js`. The router mounts directly onto `app.use('/users', usersRouter)` — no central route registry to update.

Layering within the slice still matters. Keep Express-specific concerns (`req`, `res`, `next`) strictly inside the controller. The service layer receives plain objects and returns plain objects — it never touches `req`. This makes unit testing the service trivial without spinning up an Express app. The repository layer handles all Knex/Prisma/pg calls, so swapping ORMs stays contained. Three files change per feature migration, not thirty.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/features/users/users.router.js
const { Router } = require('express');
const { getUser, createUser } = require('./users.controller');

const router = Router();
router.get('/:id', getUser);
router.post('/', createUser);
module.exports = router;

// src/app.js
const usersRouter = require('./features/users/users.router');
app.use('/users', usersRouter);$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
